      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Using `std::make_unique` combined with `std::unique_ptr` does allocate the correct semantics where the object is guaranteed to be destroyed exactly once when it goes out of scope. However, since you're still allocating on the heap in the main loop, memory from leaked or dangling pointers elsewhere in the system (like raw pointers lingering in queues) can still cause issues. Using smart pointers globally or correctly wrapping heap-allocated objects in aggregate storage prevents such lurches.",
