      "role": "user",
      "content": "right, \"lurking\" is a good way to put it. it's like these little pieces of memory just disappear into the system. if i have a queue or a buffer where these orders get stored before being executed, how do i make sure they dont just hang around indefinitely? is there a way to make sure nothing is being left behind or hidden in the buffer once it's done?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To prevent orders from hanging around indefinitely in your queue, you need to ensure the buffer itself is a finite, self-managing collection rather than just a raw array of pointers. The standard C++ practice is to wrap your queue in a smart pointer or manage ownership explicitly so that when an item is \"done,\" it transfers ownership and dereferences to a non-appropriate bucket or destructor. This prevents the system from accumulating \"hidden\" memory because the buffer's lifecycle is now tightly bound to a smart pointer's scope. If you are worried about memory leaks in high-frequency environments, consider ensuring every element in your queue is destroyed before the queue itself is destroyed, or better yet, break references from the system immediately after processing completes.",
